ribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Cawthorn in North Yorkshire or Cawthorne in West Yorkshire; both are probably named with Old English <i>cald</i> ‘cold’ (i.e. ‘exposed’) + <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn bush’. Compare   Cauthen  ,   Cauthon  ,   Cauthorn  , and   Cothern  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cawthorn","meanings":["English: variant of   Cawthorne  ."]},{"name":"Cauthron","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Cawthorne  ."]},{"name":"Cauthon","meanings":["English: variant of   Cawthorne  ."]},{"name":"Cauthorn","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Cawthorne  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Cawthon","meanings":["English: variant of   Cawthorne  ."]},{"name":"Cauthen","meanings":["English: variant of   Cawthorne  ."]},{"name":"Cothern","meanings":["English: variant of   Cawthorne  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan Crawthorne was born in 1294, in England, United Kingdom, her father, Robert Crawthorne, was 31 and her mother, Joane Worlington, was 25. She had at least 1 daughter with John De Stockhay. She died in 1360, in Hampshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1294–1360":"1294–1360","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1339–1429":"1339–1429","1264–1307":"1264–1307","1270–1351":"1270–1351","1300":"1300","1264":"1264","1351":"1351","1294":"1294","1360":"1360","1270":"1270","1429":"1429","1307":"1307","Abt 1339":"umbes 1339","1339":"1339","East Worlington, Barnstaple, Devon, England":"East Worlington, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hampshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"1294–1360":"1294–1360","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1339–1429":"1339–1429","1264–1307":"1264–1307","1270–1351":"1270–1351","1300":"1300","1264":"1264","1351":"1351","1294":"1294","1360":"1360","1270":"1270","1429":"1429","1307":"1307","Abt 1339":"noin 1339","1339":"1339","East Worlington, Barnstaple, Devon, England":"East Worlington, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Hampshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hampshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fr":{"1294–1360":"1294–1360","1300–Male":"1300–Décédé","1339–1429":"1339